What is AppArmor?

AppArmor as a critical security layer for the Linux kernel that implements Mandatory Access Control (MAC).

While the standard Linux security model (Discretionary Access Control or DAC) relies on users and groups to manage permissions, AppArmor focuses on the application itself, regardless of which user is running it.

---
The Professional Definition
"AppArmor (Application Armor) is a Linux kernel security module that allows the system administrator to restrict programs' capabilities with per-program profiles. It supplements the traditional Unix permissions model by confining applications to a limited set of resources—such as specific files, network sockets, or capabilities—effectively creating a 'sandbox' around the process."
