What is swap thrashing?
========
Swap thrashing is a high-paging state that occurs when the system's active workload exceeds its available physical RAM. This forces the kernel to constantly move pages of memory between the RAM and the Swap space (disk). Because disk I/O—even on fast NVMe drives—is significantly slower than RAM, the CPU spends the majority of its time waiting for memory pages to swap in and out rather than executing application code. This results in a total system slowdown or 'freeze'."
============
What is sysctl?
==============
sysctl as the primary interface for managing the Linux kernel's behavior dynamically. It allows you to read and modify kernel parameters at runtime without requiring a system reboot or a kernel recompilation.

Real-World Examples (Production Use-Cases)
As a Linux Admin or DevOps Engineer, you would use sysctl for System Hardening and Performance Tuning:

Networking (Performance):
net.core.somaxconn = 1024

(Increases the limit of the listen queue for accepting new TCP connections, vital for high-traffic web servers.)

Memory (Stability):
vm.swappiness = 10

(Reduces the kernel's tendency to swap, keeping more data in physical RAM.)

Security (Hardening):
net.ipv4.conf.all.accept_redirects = 0

(Disables ICMP redirects to prevent MITM attacks.)

Resource Limits:
fs.file-max = 2097152
(Increases the maximum number of file descriptors the system can open, preventing "Too many open files" errors.)

Troubleshooting & Management
sysctl -a: Lists all currently available kernel parameters (useful for discovery).

sysctl -n [parameter]: Returns only the value, which is perfect for shell scripting and automation.

sysctl -p: Reloads the configuration from /etc/sysctl.conf. This is a standard step in many Ansible or Terraform deployment scripts.
