What is kernel panic?
=========
Kernel Panic as the ultimate safety mechanism of the Linux operating system. It is the kernel's way of saying, "Something has gone so wrong that I cannot safely continue operating without risking data corruption or hardware damage."

The Professional Definition
"A Kernel Panic is a critical system error that occurs when the Linux kernel encounters a fatal condition from which it cannot recover. At this point, the kernel stops all execution, flashes the keyboard lights (on some hardware), and displays an error message on the console. It is the Linux equivalent of the 'Blue Screen of Death' (BSOD) in Windows."
========
What is journaling file system?
============
Journaling File System as a robust file system that maintains a special log (a journal) to track changes before they are permanently committed to the main filesystem. This is primarily a data integrity and fast recovery feature.

The Professional Definition
"A journaling file system is designed to prevent filesystem corruption in the event of a system crash or power failure. It works by recording the 'intent' of a disk write operation in a dedicated area called the journal before performing the actual write. If the system fails mid-operation, the kernel can simply replay the journal to complete the task or roll it back, ensuring the filesystem remains in a consistent state."

=========
 What is OOM Killer?
============
"The OOM Killer is a kernel mechanism that activates when the system is dangerously low on available memory (RAM + Swap). Because the Linux kernel often 'overcommits' memory—promising more RAM to applications than it actually has—it sometimes runs into a situation where it cannot satisfy a memory request. To prevent the entire kernel from crashing (a Kernel Panic), the OOM Killer selects and terminates a specific process to reclaim memory."

1. How the "Victim" is Selected (OOM Score)
The kernel doesn't just pick a process at random. It uses an algorithm to calculate an oom_score for every running process. The process with the highest score is killed first.

Factors that increase the score:

High Resident Memory: The more RAM the process is using, the more likely it is to be targeted.

Process Age: Younger processes are sometimes targeted more than older, established ones.

Non-Root User: Processes run by the root user are given a slight protection (a lower score).

Where to find it:
You can actually see the score for any process (e.g., PID 1234) in the /proc filesystem:
cat /proc/1234/oom_score

2. The Concept of "Overcommit"
To sound like a senior admin, you must explain why this happens.
Linux uses Memory Overcommit. Think of it like an airline that overbooks a flight, assuming not everyone will show up. The kernel grants memory requests from apps, betting that they won't all use 100% of that memory at the exact same time. When they do, the "flight is full," and the OOM Killer starts "bumping" passengers.

3. Managing the OOM Killer in Production
In a DevOps environment, you don't always want the kernel to decide who dies. You can influence the OOM Killer:

OOM Score Adjust (oom_score_adj): You can manually lower a process's score to protect it. For example, you might protect your SSH daemon or a critical Database so they are the last to be killed.

Sysctl Tuning:

vm.overcommit_memory: You can change this to "2" to disable overcommit, making the system refuse new memory requests once RAM is full (this prevents the OOM Killer but might make apps crash earlier).

vm.panic_on_oom: If set to 1, the system will simply perform a Kernel Panic instead of trying to kill a process.
